<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">Understanding eReturns</h3>

<p class="govuk-body">
  An eReturn is the electronic equivalent of "cashing up" at the end of the day. It summarises all payments received, broken down by payment method and fund, so that finance officers can verify that everything balances. This is a critical daily control in council income management.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">Generate an eReturn</h3>

<ol class="govuk-list govuk-list--number govuk-list--spaced">
  <li>
    <strong>Navigate to eReturns</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      From the admin portal, navigate to the eReturns section. This is where you'll find the daily reconciliation tools.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Select today's date</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Select the current date to generate an eReturn for today's transactions. You should see the payment you made in Step 1 included in the totals.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Review the breakdown</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      The eReturn shows:
    </p>
    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
      <li><strong>Payment method totals</strong> — card payments, bank transfers, cash, cheques</li>
      <li><strong>Fund totals</strong> — amounts allocated to each council fund</li>
      <li><strong>Transaction count</strong> — number of individual transactions</li>
      <li><strong>Suspense movements</strong> — items moved in or out of suspense</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Generate the eReturn</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Click to generate the eReturn. This creates the official record for the day. In a production environment, this would feed into the council's general ledger and bank reconciliation processes.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>

<div class="govuk-inset-text">
  <strong>Why this matters:</strong> Daily eReturns are a key financial control. They ensure that all income received is properly accounted for and that the income management system balances with the bank. Any discrepancies flagged here are investigated immediately rather than discovered during month-end or audit.
</div>

